tspan.tspan: The Parasitic Centipede
An intrepid young wolf was out in search of its place in the
world, then, without any warning, a horrible parasitic
centipede dropped out of a tree, landed on the wolf's back,
and latched on with every one of its barbed legs.
It hurt, and it hurt more when the wolf scratched at it. The
centipede said "If you try to remove me again, I will sting
you with venom, and kill you", so the wolf stopped
scratching, and the pain stopped. The wolf had a patient
character, so as soon as the wolf accepted that the
centipede could not be removed, the two became friends.
The wolf and the parasitic centipede had many interesting
conversations. The centipede told the wolf that there are
tasty grubs who live in rotted trees, and it was true, and
the wolf found the grubs in a tree, and ate them, and the
centipede enjoyed their flavor in the wolf's blood. The wolf
and the parasitic centipede enjoyed the grubs together.
Eventually the wolf found a perfect tree for the parasitic
centipede to lay its eggs in, and so after all of their travels,
it was time for the parasitic centipede to leave the wolf,
but the centipede noticed, "When I let go, I wont be able to
sting you any more." The wolf answered. "Of course. I will
be pleased with that." The centipede asked, "But that
means you could chase me and stomp on me." And the wolf
answered, "You've been honorable. I will not hurt you. It's
safe to let go." And the centipede could feel in its feet that
it was true.
So the centipede pried up its many barbed claws out of the
wolf's back, and jumped away. The wolf stood and watched
it crawl along the ground, and noticed that the centipede
had become enormous in the time after it had first
attached, it now looked more like a giant caterpillar.
The centipede safely reached its tree, and laid many eggs
in it, which grew into new centipedes, who eventually
found their own wolves, and the cycle continued.
Eventually, cycle after cycle, after a million years, wolves
learned to use centipedes and their venom during their
hunts, and centipede was allowed to live in wolf's den.
Wolf and centipede could no longer imagine living apart.
It's rare in life that we deliberately practice Negotiation, yet our creative ability in dialogs of social
compromise determines basically everything. It's needed whenever there's disagreement, power,
trade, collective decisions to be made, it essentially is the core skill of Politics (the fact that people
don't think this is part of the reason everything is toilet today), and even Love will end up needing it.
The situations in which it naturally emerges in daily life tend not to be fun, so we avoid it, we don't
train, and when it fails, all sorts of collective idiocy unfolds, usually some form of war.
Optimal Weave 0.1 aims to provide a special space where practicing negotiation will be fun.
It does this primarily by being a game. Games are places where experimentation is safe and easy. The
genuine real life dramas in which negotiation is naturally called for are not games, and so they make
poor learning experiences, punishing creative risktaking with permanent injuries, inspiring avoidance
and conservatism, forbidding experimentation.
It's also much more transparent than life is: Every goal, ability, choice and consequence is simple and
clear, so when the game ends, the the outcomes can easily be interpreted and learned from.
There are no other games like this one. There are lots of reasons for that, but we don't think any of
them are serious. Cohabitive games are able to model a much wider variety of characters,
relationships, and stories than purely competitive or purely cooperative games can. On the other side
of our labor we will (eventually) find a genre of games that are much richer than what came before.
